Heavy rain deluged some drought-hit areas as Congress began

working on a package of relief for America's farmers, and farmers in Kentucky today greeted the arrival of the first shipment of hay airlifted free from Oregon.
The Agriculture Department, meanwhile, issued a report predicting severe damage to the harvest from the drought.
The drought has dried up pastures, forcing livestock farmers to go far afield for hay.
The hay that arrived in Kentuky today will be stored at a fairgrounds, and distributed next week by lottery to farmers, who will pay for the hay, officials said.
